climbing a hill. Climbing hill is one's spiritual 
sadhana. Reaching the to=
p is liberation. Different people climb the hill from 
different sides and =
using different paths. There may be trees with nice fruits 
on the sides of=
 the road. They are siddhis or special abilities.
=C2=A0
If one gets distra=
cted, starts climbing the trees and collecting fruits, one's 
journey gets =
delayed and one may not reach the top. That is why Vasishtha says a 
seeker=
 of Self does not pursue any siddhis.
=C2=A0
But if some fruits fall in one=
's lap by themselves, one can keep them. 
Similarly, siddhis that come to o=
ne by themselves can be accepted by a seeker of 
Self.
=C2=A0
Now an import=
ant distinction:
=C2=A0
There are some trees that are found at lower altitu=
des also, but some really 
special trees are found at very high altitudes o=
nly. If one has such a fruit, it 
shows that one has climbed great heights.=
 Similarly, some siddhis do not mean 
much, but some siddhis are very speci=
al and only really elevated sadhakas can 
obtain them (whether by trying or=
 without trying). If a sadhakas demonstrates 
such a siddhi, you can see th=
at one progressed a lot. However, the key is that 
one who climbed the same=
 or more distance may not have that or any other fruit. 

=C2=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=
